<div id="review_1771205484" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1771205484" />
    <a title="Raquel" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/60099374-raquel"><img alt="Raquel" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1601211766p2/60099374.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1771205484?book_show_action=true">Sep 29, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Raquel" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Raquel" href="/user/show/60099374-raquel">Raquel</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="did not like it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">did not like it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 7503013925764" href="/book/show/30110280-1q84">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/60099374-raquel?shelf=asian-lit">asian-lit</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/60099374-raquel?shelf=magical-realism">magical-realism</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/60099374-raquel?shelf=haruki-murakami">haruki-murakami</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1771205484" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6996307188658701942">{Notice: I’ve only read Parts 1 and 2 as the Spanish edition is divided that way and Part 3 is edited as another book}<br/><br/><i>«If you can&apos;t understand it without an explanation, you can&apos;t understand it with an explanation.»</i><br/><br/>It&apos;s the first and only Murakami book that I didn’t like. And I don’t know how to deal with it. I&apos;m confused because he’s <b>always</b> been my favourite author and except for the essay <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/2195464.What_I_Talk_About_When_I_Talk_About_Running' title='What I Talk About When I Talk About Running by Haruki Murakami' rel='nofollow noopener'> What I Talk About When I Talk About Running</a>, I&apos;ve always finished all his books. And I ended up loving th</span>
  <span id="freeText6996307188658701942" style="display:none">{Notice: I’ve only read Parts 1 and 2 as the Spanish edition is divided that way and Part 3 is edited as another book}<br /><br /><i>«If you can't understand it without an explanation, you can't understand it with an explanation.»</i><br /><br />It's the first and only Murakami book that I didn’t like. And I don’t know how to deal with it. I'm confused because he’s <b>always</b> been my favourite author and except for the essay <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/2195464.What_I_Talk_About_When_I_Talk_About_Running" title="What I Talk About When I Talk About Running by Haruki Murakami" rel="nofollow noopener"> What I Talk About When I Talk About Running</a>, I've always finished all his books. And I ended up loving the story, the characters, the narrative... Murakami is part of my personality and I wouldn’t be the same without Murakami's books. So this review is probably the one that costs me the most to write in my life. Murakami made me love literature again when I was 16 years old and enjoy again those reading moments before going to sleep, but this book seemed insufferable to me. Well, no, I'm going to clarify a little more: the second part has seemed insufferable to me. I needed answers, that something would happen, I needed to be interested in the novel as I’d been interested in the first part, but no. Nothing of that happened.<br /><br />I loved <b>Aomame</b> from the beginning for being a different character to what I am used to in the works of the Japanese writer, and I liked very much to see represented as a professional killer, a feminist {although she didn’t consider herself as such}, a strong and independent woman and different from the usual female characters of the author. Maybe <b>Tengo</b> is the character we are most used to knowing, and I liked it equally. I liked the fact that the stories were intermingled and that there were such beautiful coincidences building little by little, as only Haruki knows how to build them.<br />But all the things that I liked, I stopped enjoying them in the second part. In the moments of greatest climax, Murakami just cut the whole scene and created a constant anticlimax. The last chapters became very slow and nothing interesting happened that was worthwhile for me to continue reading the book. He hasn’t given answers to most questions posed by the novel, and the conclusion of the parallel worlds didn’t get to hook me at all.<br /><br />It will seem silly, but this book has broken my heart. I don’t think I’m gonna read the third and last part ever {or at least in the next few months}<br /><br />- ESP -<br />{Aviso: solamente he leído los Libros 1 y 2 tal como está editado <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/10357575.1Q84" title="1Q84 by Haruki Murakami" rel="nofollow noopener"> 1Q84</a> por Maxi Tusquets}<br /><br /><i>«Conviertes lo que has visto en palabras y lo reconstruyes. De esa forma confirmas tu sitio en el mundo como ser humano.»</i><br /><br />Es el primer y único libro de Murakami que no me ha gustado. Y no sé cómo lidiar con ello. Estoy confusa porque <b>siempre</b> ha sido mi autor favorito y excepto por el ensayo <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/7997569.De_qu__hablo_cuando_hablo_de_correr" title="De qué hablo cuando hablo de correr by Haruki Murakami" rel="nofollow noopener"> De qué hablo cuando hablo de correr</a>, siempre he terminado todos sus libros. Y los he terminado amando la historia, los personajes, la narrativa. Murakami forma parte de mi personalidad y yo no sería la misma sin los libros de Murakami. Así que esta reseña es probablemente la reseña que más me cueste escribir en mi vida. Murakami hizo que volviera a amar la literatura cuando tenía 16 años y volver a disfrutar de esos momentos de lectura antes de irme a dormir, pero este libro me ha parecido insufrible. Bueno, no, voy a matizar un poco más: la segunda parte me ha parecido insufrible. Necesitaba respuestas, que pasara algo, que me interesara la novela al igual que me había interesado la primera parte, pero no. No pasó nada de eso.<br /><br />Me encantó el personaje de <b>Aomame</b> desde el principio por ser un personaje diferente a lo que estoy acostumbrada en las obras del escritor japonés, y me gustaba mucho ver representada una asesina a sueldo, feminista {aunque ella no se considerara como tal}, una mujer fuerte e independiente y diferente a los personajes femeninos del autor. Quizás <b>Tengo</b> es el personaje al que más estamos habituados a conocer, y me gustó igualmente. Me gustó el hecho de que las historias se entremezclasen, que hubiera esas coincidencias tan bonitas construyéndose poco a poco, como sólo Haruki sabe construirlas. Pero todas las cosas que me gustaban, dejaron de hacerlo en la segunda parte. En los momentos de mayor clímax de la obra, cortaba de raíz y creaba un anticlímax constante. Los últimos capítulos se me hicieron lentísimos y no ha pasado nada interesante que mereciera la pena para que yo siga leyendo la obra. No ha dado respuestas a la mayoría de preguntas que plantea la novela, y la conclusión de los mundos paralelos no llegó a engancharme.<br /><br />Os parecerá una tontería, pero este libro me ha roto el corazón. No creo que termine la tercera y última parte nunca {o al menos en los próximos meses}.</span>
  <a data-text-id="6996307188658701942" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


