<div id="review_229092376" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/229092376" />
    <a title="Susan" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1655341-susan"><img alt="Susan" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1237599293p2/1655341.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/229092376?book_show_action=true">Oct 30, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Susan" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Susan" href="/user/show/1655341-susan">Susan</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1655341-susan?shelf=novels">novels</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer229092376" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10916338581722565592">1Q84 weighs a couple of pounds and has 944 pages in the hardback edition, but the length and poundage are as nothing compared to its looney gravitational pull. Murakami draws us into a world with two moons, a world that may contain respect but is without overt expressions of love. I suspect that Murakami exerts such a strong pull in the original through his strange prose and use of physical details. Even in English, the style is simple and pictorial, like that of a graphic novel where each actio</span>
  <span id="freeText10916338581722565592" style="display:none">1Q84 weighs a couple of pounds and has 944 pages in the hardback edition, but the length and poundage are as nothing compared to its looney gravitational pull. Murakami draws us into a world with two moons, a world that may contain respect but is without overt expressions of love. I suspect that Murakami exerts such a strong pull in the original through his strange prose and use of physical details. Even in English, the style is simple and pictorial, like that of a graphic novel where each action takes place in a fully realized setting, and the characters are given over to interior monologues and intensely honest conversations.There is always something ominous in 1Q84, where the cultural background is American and European and the characters are Japanese but deeply alienated from society. As in Murakami's other novels, this divergence makes for a fascinating conflict in practically every word. <br /><br />The two main characters, a fitness instructor named Aomame whose name means green pea, and Tengo, a teacher of math and an aspiring novelist, each enter a strange world dominated by a cult and a cadre of "Little People," the latter, beyond good and evil. Once the sinister forces are defeated, the novel transforms itself from an odd fairy tale with helping spirits and boogey men into a conventional love story. Throughout, there are references to Western music, literature, film, and philosophy, and Japanese culture is depicted as fiercely misogynistic and bitterly repressive. This is a daring book packaged, with more filling than necessary, as a fantasy.</span>
  <a data-text-id="10916338581722565592" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


