<div id="review_3074191646" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3074191646" />
    <a title="Cátia Vieira" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/20910956-c-tia-vieira"><img alt="Cátia Vieira" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1620057474p2/20910956.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3074191646?book_show_action=true">Jan 15, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Cátia Vieira" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Cátia Vieira" href="/user/show/20910956-c-tia-vieira">Cátia Vieira</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback " href="/book/show/20935099-1q84">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3074191646" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13844090540916711820">Murakami, I am really sad to say that I am slightly glad to be done with this massive volume! Book 1 and Book 2: done! Book 3 to go! The Japanese writer, Haruki Murakami, is my favorite male writer alive. But, as I said, when I posted about 1Q84 Book 1, I can see flaws in Murakami’s writing even though I am a fan of his work. I also told you that I didn’t want to write a proper review until I finish the book entirely so I still need to read Book 3 before sharing my final thoughts.<br/><br/>Here’s a quick </span>
  <span id="freeText13844090540916711820" style="display:none">Murakami, I am really sad to say that I am slightly glad to be done with this massive volume! Book 1 and Book 2: done! Book 3 to go! The Japanese writer, Haruki Murakami, is my favorite male writer alive. But, as I said, when I posted about 1Q84 Book 1, I can see flaws in Murakami’s writing even though I am a fan of his work. I also told you that I didn’t want to write a proper review until I finish the book entirely so I still need to read Book 3 before sharing my final thoughts.<br /><br />Here’s a quick summary of what I gathered throughout these 800 pages: We’re in Tokyo, in 1Q84 (yes, this is a dystopian novel!) and a lot is happening during the fictionalized year of 1984 (Hi, Orwell 🙌)The plot follows the lives of two characters: Tengo and Aomame. Initially, they have nothing in common but, during Book 2, their storylines come together. After a long and strong story that explores abuse, punishment and redemption, the characters notice a second moon which reminds them of the alternate reality in which they’re living.<br /><br />Although I find the whole concept incredibly interesting I couldn’t stand Tengo and his pedophilic behaviour. I thought 'Maybe in Book 2 it won’t be just as bad'. <br /><br />For more reviews, follow me on Instagram @booksturnyouon.</span>
