    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_529134030" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/529134030" />
    <a title="James" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/6022914-james"><img alt="James" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1421168922p2/6022914.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/529134030?book_show_action=true">Feb 07, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="James" class="user" itemprop="url" name="James" href="/user/show/6022914-james">James</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780099549062" href="/book/show/15822556-1q84">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6022914-james?shelf=i-own-paperback">i-own-paperback</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6022914-james?shelf=i-own-ebook">i-own-ebook</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6022914-james?shelf=science-fiction">science-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6022914-james?shelf=translated">translated</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6022914-james?shelf=1001-books">1001-books</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6022914-james?shelf=book-club">book-club</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer529134030" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9361757632583075897">This is a strange review as I&apos;ve only read book one so far.<br/><br/>1Q84 Book One was our work book club choice this month as we assumed it was the first in a three book series, but having read to the end of book one it just stops dead. No real build up, no reveal, no twist. Just stops dead. Clearly we now realise that books one and two are actually two volumes in a single novel. They should probably be read back-to-back rather than reading book one now and book two later (probably next year for me now).</span>
  <span id="freeText9361757632583075897" style="display:none">This is a strange review as I've only read book one so far.<br /><br />1Q84 Book One was our work book club choice this month as we assumed it was the first in a three book series, but having read to the end of book one it just stops dead. No real build up, no reveal, no twist. Just stops dead. Clearly we now realise that books one and two are actually two volumes in a single novel. They should probably be read back-to-back rather than reading book one now and book two later (probably next year for me now).<br /><br />Consequently, it's hard to rate it. I have absolutely no idea where this book is going, or even much idea what's going on. And that's to be expected now I know I haven't read the whole book. I'm going to say I liked it, but I'm not <i>really</i> liking it and I don't think it's awesome. Yet. I reserve the right to change this when I get to book two later on. (Book three is a whole different topic, that does appear to be designed to be read as a separate - sequel - book.)<br /><br />It's a very interesting novel though. Alternating between two viewpoint characters of Aomame (not to be confused with edamame) - a fitness instructor <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[with a sideline in assassinating abusive men <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span> who climbs down an access stairway from a freeway to find herself in an alternate 1984, which she terms 1Q84 - and Tengo - a maths teacher who wants to be an author who ends up rewriting a novel by a young girl for a literary competition. Both characters find themselves drawn into an increasingly strange alternate reality.<br /><br />Along the way, we are introduced to a women's refuge that resolves abuse in a somewhat final way, a farming community that has become a religious cult, a dyslexic seventeen year old girl who has written a potentially prize-winning story, an editor and a professor who both have their own reasons to have the story win the prize, and a slow reveal of the connections between nearly all the characters.<br /><br />On the downsides, the book has a couple of obsessions. Murakami seems overly keen to describe the breasts of almost all the main (female) characters in the novel (often repeatedly) - Aomame's are too small, Ayumi's are larger, and Fuka-Eri's are perfect (well she is seventeen) and look great in a sweater. I was glad he drew the line at describing the Dowager's. Coupled with Aomame's obsession with having sex with balding middle-aged men (Sean Connery is her ideal) with the 'right-shaped' head, it starts to feel a little like Murakami is trying to slip his own fantasies into an otherwise fascinating story...</span>
  <a data-text-id="9361757632583075897" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


