<div id="review_867080788" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/867080788" />
    <a title="Kitty G Books" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/19126246-kitty-g-books"><img alt="Kitty G Books" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1643144344p2/19126246.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/867080788?book_show_action=true">Feb 27, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Kitty G Books" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Kitty G Books" href="/user/show/19126246-kitty-g-books">Kitty G Books</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9781846554070" href="/book/show/9911160-1q84">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer867080788" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12700723332919371531">This is a highly interesting story in all sense of the word and I cannot think how to begin to describe all of the feelings I encountered whilst reading this. This was my first Murakami read and I have to confess I knew next to nothing about it, or him, or George Orwell&apos;s 1984 which is referenced a lot in this novel, however despite these challenges I did end up really enjoying the entire two books and I will certainly be picking up book 3 when I can to find out how it all draws to a close.<br/><br/>The s</span>
  <span id="freeText12700723332919371531" style="display:none">This is a highly interesting story in all sense of the word and I cannot think how to begin to describe all of the feelings I encountered whilst reading this. This was my first Murakami read and I have to confess I knew next to nothing about it, or him, or George Orwell's 1984 which is referenced a lot in this novel, however despite these challenges I did end up really enjoying the entire two books and I will certainly be picking up book 3 when I can to find out how it all draws to a close.<br /><br />The story itself is hard to describe, being told from two points of view, Aomame and Tengo. These two characters are integral to the plot and they are both so meticulously detailed and scrutanising in the way that they view the world that reading through their eyes is a very strange experience and truly brings you into their new world in an entirely different way.<br /><br />Tengo is a writer of fiction who is struggling to find his own vision and create a masterwork to give him a 'name' in the literary world. He has a passion for Mathematics and teaches at a local school during the week. He enjoys the company of older women, finding no love for those who are of his age or younger, and taking solace in the time he spends with his older, married girlfriend each week. He is a careful character and doesn't like to get involved in anything he doesn't see as morally right or unsuspicious. However the story he is a part of makes these decisions hard for him, and he crosses some lines that he may not normally have done so...<br /><br />Aomame is a highly trained muscle therapist and she has become rather renowned for her skills in the trade. She is a lonely individual who has few friends and little time for fun, more contemplation. Her style and sexual partners are very much constant throughout the text, however she does have a longing for someone else who always seems to be out of her grasp. Working as a muscle therapist is but one of her jobs, the other being of a far more sensitive matter. She helps to make the world better, or so she tries to convince herself...<br /><br />Fuka-Eri is another key character from the story although we don't actually see from her point of view. She is a cryptic character and throughout the entire novel she seems to know far more than she lets on or that she is able to confess to the main characters. She is a very capable, bright and knowledgeable character and although she lacks certain skills she is able to come across as a pivotal person in the novel.<br /><br />Overall one of the aspects I truly enjoyed was the writing which is on a whole new, mystical level from most other books I have read. Murakami is clearly very talented and even when I truly couldn't grasp how everything would come together at all, I found that I loved the writing and character development enough to keep being sucked back into the world without question. <br /><br />I also loved the character development, much of which is illustrated through the thoughts and contemplation of the two main characters who are, in their own way, critical, analytic, and clever. Their perception of the world of 1Q84 makes it all the more enthralling to read about and all the more magical and captivating to be a part of as you read. The style of narration was truly ensnaring and I loved that element. <br /><br />There is a mystical and fantastical element to the world which I didn't know was a part of the novel but I did absolutely love it as this is what I love in books and the adult writing brought a much more complex tone to the magic and made it hard to define or interpret, yet still exciting enough to encaptured my thoughts.<br /><br />On the whole I would say that if you enjoy adult writing, mystical and magical ideas, well-crafted plot and a superb style of storytelling then this is a brilliant read, the only reason that I took off a star is that the ending leaves much open, and I hope that when I read book 3 these questions raised by the ending will be answered and I will be able to grant book 3 a 5* rating instead of 4*s</span>
  <a data-text-id="12700723332919371531" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


